added timestamp, see [commit #59ded27](#!/osrf/drcsim/commits/59ded27fba1736727ed3c244f03e6f6cda3b18ae).

In your `AtlasSimInterfaceState` subscriber, are you using `tcpnodelay`?  If not, see [this bit of code](#!/osrf/drcsim/src/3f4f90878a7ceb1b990264bc5e02652fe457e003/ros/atlas_msgs/pub_atlas_state.cpp?at=default#cl-109), enabling `tcpnodelay` may help you reduce the amount of jitter in network communication.  For example, something similar to below:

~~~
  // ros topic subscribtions
  ros::SubscribeOptions asiStateSo =
    ros::SubscribeOptions::create<atlas_msgs::AtlasSimInterfaceState>(
    "/atlas/atlas_sim_interface_state", 100, SetAtlasSimInterfaceState,
    ros::VoidPtr(), rosnode->getCallbackQueue());
  asiStateSo.transport_hints =
    ros::TransportHints().reliable().tcpNoDelay(true);
  ros::Subscriber subASIState = rosnode->subscribe(asiStateSo);
~~~

John
